<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>AFS0020</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-align:right; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0020</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from the socialist Educational Association</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In this submission we argue that there is no evidence that sponsored academies have proved more effective than maintained schools in raising standards. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Anecdotes about individual schools do not constitute evidence. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We further argue that there is evidence to suggest that sponsored academies have not contributed to closing attainment gaps </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">making possible (as own admission authority schools)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">more</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> socio-economic selection they are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> likely to make this situation worse.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We agree with the recent statement by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Andreas Schleicher</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The UK demonstrates that increasing school choice and competition does not improve standards”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We maintain that the p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rocess of academy conversion and the es</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tablishment of free schools has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> been characterised by a serious democratic deficit, by a substantial waste of public money and by entirely unproductive levels of conflict within local communities.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We consider tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Secretary of State’s approach to intervention is wholly inadequate and demonstrates a failure to understand how the process of school improvement actually works. We consider that there is much more to be learned from the success of collaborative prog</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rammes such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">London and City Challenge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee’s terms of reference assume the continuation and the further expansion of the academy programme. SEA argues that this is not a sustainable position and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that a new settlement is required whic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h addresses the confusion and fragmentation that now characterises the English school system.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Evidence</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Socialist Educational Association is the educational </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">affiliate of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the Labour Party.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> SEA members include MPs, school governors, local Councillors, teachers, students</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">parents. More information about the SEA can be found at </span><a href="http://www.socialisteducation.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.socialisteducation.org.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">happy to pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ovide further detail to the Committee either in writing or orally on any of the issues raised in this statement. SEA can be contacted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><a href="mailto:socialisteducation@virginmedia.com"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">socialisteducation@virginmedia.com</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The impact of academ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ies on attainment</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is now </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ample</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> evidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which shows</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that there is no significant difference between the performance of sponsored academies and similar maintained schools –</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">both in absolute terms and in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rate of improvement.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Attempts to argue otherwise, including those by the DfE, are consistently flawed because they do not compare sponsored academies with similar schools. The work of Henry Stewart</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> demonstrate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> this very clearly.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It has also been demonstrated that improveme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nt in a significant number of sponsored academies has been achieved </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">only t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hrough the use o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> non GCSE qualifications (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e.g.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the recent NFER/LGA analysis of academy school performance)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.2 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Recent research by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Stephen Machin and Olmo Silva</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has demonstrated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that academies have not contributed to “closing the gap”, arguing that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">chools that converted to academies between 2002 and 2007 improved their overall GCSEs results by further raising the attainments of students in the top half of the ability distributi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">on, and in particular pupils in the top 20%. Conversely, we find little evidence that academies helped pupils in the bottom 10% and 20% of the ability distribution. Finally, we find little evidence that late converters (2008 and 2009) had any beneficial ef</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">fects on pupils of any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ability.”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In SEA’s view, one important reason for the failure of the school system to close the gap between the lowest achievers and the rest has been the level of socio-economic segregation that persists in the English school sy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stem. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There has never been a genuinely level playing field for schools in England. Subtle (or not so subtle) variations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in governance, admissions policies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, specialism</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, religious affiliation etc. have helped to create a local pecking order of schools.  The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> advent of academies and free schools has made this situation worse. Too many schools manipulate their admissions to gain a more favoured intake to the advantage of “sharp-elbowed” parents who know how to work the system. The scale of this problem has just</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> been confirmed by the research of Stephen Gorand at Durham University</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> who concluded that:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“any differentiated type of school - including faith-based, foundation, and fee-paying - tends to be linked to higher local levels of segregation. On the other hand, maintained, non-selective, 'bog-standard' schools are strongly and unambiguously linked to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> both lower segregation and a further decline in segregation of all types over time. If you want less segregation, do not have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">different types of school”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We know that a key issue for English schools is the tail of underachievement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> In 2012 OECD </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">identi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fied a number of system level issues that contribute to this kind of underachievement. Of particular relevance here are the recommendations to “a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">void early tracking (i.e selection, setting and streaming) and defer student selection to upper secondary” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“manage school choice to avoid segregation and increased inequities”. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although in theory there is equal access to schools for all, in practice we are seeing more selection and social segregation in the English school system. In OECD’s view this will lea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d to lower levels of achievement in the system as a whole. </span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[iv]</a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Establishing Academy and Free Schools</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SEA argues that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> process of establishing academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and free </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">schools has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">characterised by a very serious democratic deficit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by a substantial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">waste of public money</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and by entirely unproductive levels of conflict within local communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Democratic Deficit</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Opportunities for local communities to have any meaningful say in how schools are planned and run have been substantially and unacce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ptably reduced. Decisions on opening, closing and changing the nature of schools are now taken largely by central government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It is sometimes forgotten that education is of concern to the whole of society and is not just a matter for those directly involve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The process is often secretive and is open to the charge of cronyism. It seems to be geared primarily to meeting political targets – i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the number of academy conversions and the number of free schools regardless of quality. It is very clear that some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">promoters/ sponsors of schools have been inadequate and driven by inappropriate ideological or commercial considerations.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The proposals of particular interest groups (often a minority group) are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">often </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">accepted regardless of their effect on others – as long</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as they are politically acceptable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The presumption is that market forces will decide which schools succeed and which do not. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">However it is not possible to run an education system as a market </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">without having a damaging impact on some schools and pupils. Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is is why school systems need to be planned through a democratic process in which all views can be heard.</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[v]</a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is also a growing democratic deficit within schools. In many academy chains, schools are subject to the central management of the chain in ways</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that would be entirely unacceptable in local authority schools. They are not always </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">permitted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to have their own governing body and consequently the role of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">parents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> local communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in governance is significantly diminished. This downgrading of the place of parent governors can be found in other academies and free schools.</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[vi]</a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Waste</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The most obvious example of wasting resources is the opening of free schools where there is already a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> surplus of places. At a time when there is a growing shortage of primary places in parts of the country, this is inexcusable.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Public Accounts Committee has clearly documented the waste of public money by the Academies programme amounting to about £1 billion. A significant part of this was in effect bribes to schools to convert. It also arose from the creation of duplicate man</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">agement systems – for example much of the funding work of the EFA could be done by local authorities at little extra cost. There have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> been notorious examples of inappropriate extravagance by some academy chains and indeed by some individual schools wh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ere there is no longer any real oversight in place.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conflict</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Arguments over school status have distracted schools, parents and teachers in many areas from their core business. Relationships have been damaged and time and energy has been wasted in unpr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oductive arguments, leading in some cases to industrial action. At times it can feel that such conflict is welcomed by government because it enables it to denigrate those who disagree – the “enemies of progress” argument. The deliberate provoking of confli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ct across the country seems however an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">appropriate way for a government to carry on.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Intervention by the Secretary of State</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The secretary of state is now directly responsible for the performance of about three thousand academies and free schools across </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the country. This includes responsibility for not just their academic performance but their financial probity, a range of issues relating to individual pupils and families and their adherence to a wide range of regulations. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">All this is widely accepted as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unsustainable in both practical terms and in terms of the unacceptable centralisation of power in a single person’s hands. It means that there is no way for the voice of parents and local communities to be heard – as can be seen in the way opposition to fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rced academisation and to particular sponsors has been consistently ignored</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is now the situation that many schools are effectively accountable to no one but themselves. They are formally accountable to the Secretary of State but it is clear that the DfE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> does not have the capacity to identify issues at an early stage – this takes local knowledge drawn not just from data but from regular contact with local communities and agencies. Nor is it in a position to provide what David Wolfe </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">QC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">describes as “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">a more</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> subtle and supportive regime of external intervention to encourage school improvement.</span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[vii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">Ofsted and the DfE can only offer intervention of a very crude and high level kind</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal"> as has been demonstrated by the recent issue of warning notices to failing academie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">s. These show no capacity to engage with schools at any detailed level nor any desire to understand their issues in detail. DfE intervention seems to be confined </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">to a threat to enforce a change of governance and/ or sponsor. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">The recent proposals by the S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">ecretary of State to establish 8 regional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">commissioners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal"> to be responsible for monitoring academies and free schools will be in no way adequate. With an average of 400 schools each (a figure that is presumably expected to rise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal"> they</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal"> will be no more effective than the DfE is now. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">It seems </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">remarkable, at this time of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal"> financial stringency, to establish a whole parallel bureaucracy working only with some schools.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">On the ground, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">he provision of support for school improvement has been ser</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">iously undermined in recent years. Partly this has been a result of cuts in funding. But it has also been based on a belief that schools can and should manage their own improvement, if necessary in collaboration with other schools. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">There is no doubt that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">teachers can and do learn a lot from one another. But it is not realistic to expect schools to keep up with both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">current research and debate and with best practice across the country. There is therefore a need for people and institutions that are in a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">position to take a broad view based on research and experience of a wide range of schools. This could traditionally be found in local authority services and in higher education. Both of these are now under sustained attack.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">It is also clear that school to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">school initiatives are patchy. The RSA Academies Commission found that many outstanding schools are not making the contribution to school improvement that is expected of them. </span><a name="_ednref8"></a><a href="#_edn8">[viii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">The distribution of teaching schools is also patchy with no certainty that a sc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">hool in need of support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal"> access it.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Middle Tier</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would argue that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">managing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the establishment and monitoring of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">all schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> requires a democratically accountable local tier of governance. This needs to be responsible not for running schools b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ut for the key functions of planning, commissioning and monitoring. None of these are now being done effectively by central government. Privatising these functions to unaccountable chains and sponsors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has been shown to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inimical to the concept of public </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and open to abuse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The purpose of this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> middle tier should be to take functions away from Whitehall and exercise them at a local level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to reduce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> levels of school autonomy that have been in place now for many years.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The key purpose of a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">democratically accountable middle tier is to provide broad educational leadership across an area. It should champion the interests of children and families and should ensure that the vested interests of schools do not obstruct the delivery of an educationa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l entitlement for all children and young people.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It should:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">identify and plan to meet changing demand for school places </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure that their areas have the range of schools that will meet the needs and aspirations of all local people.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commission post 16 pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ovision across both school and college sectors working with and through school/college partnerships </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure that a common admissions system pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vides fair access for all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">monitor the performance of schools including academic performance, financial systems</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and adherence to national standards including equalities duties.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with schools, establish and implement a fair funding formula covering all state funded schools in their area.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">intervene where there is clear evidence of inadequate performance including requ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iring changes in the governance and leadership of schools if other interventions have been unsuccessful.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">promote school improvement in collaboration with School Partnerships.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">identify pup</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ils with additional needs and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ensure that these are met by schools. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provide for all pupils independent specialist careers advice and guidance. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Academy chains cannot themselves </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a middle tier authority. They cover only a minority of schools, range from just a couple of schools to well over 50, have no geographical un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ity and are wholly unaccountable to either parents or voters.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We would argue that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">all schools should be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> independent legal entities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">which is not the case for sponsored academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">schools should be free to identify external support from any app</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ropriate source</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n academy chain could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">then</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be one of these options. But we doubt that chains working with only a very small number of schools actually have much to offer.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Alternatives to Sponsored Academy Status</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">present 44% of secondary and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">46% of primary sponsored academies are either inadequate or require improvement, it is difficult to maintain the view that sponsored academy status is a uniquely effective route to improvement. There have clearly been successful sponsored academies but to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">argue purely by anecdote is not enough.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SEA would argue that the most effective path to school improvement is through the support of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">successful</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> local schools that are facing similar challenges. We would also argue that the engagement of an experienced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">adviser with both the time and the ability to work with the school in depth can make an important contribution. This is the message of the London and City Challenges which had a huge effect on standards in important parts of the country. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It was also the me</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ssage of the Select Committee’s recent report on school partnerships.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We suggest that there is much in that report which is relevant to this inquiry as well.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.3.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are also examples of tighter school partnerships and federations which have been effect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ive in raising standards. W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e are not opposed to external partners making a contribution to school improvement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> either with individual schools or with partnerships. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">But we do not think that schools and their local communities are best served by being requir</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed to adopt the status of sponsored academy, with the loss of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> democracy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and autonomy that this involves.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Fragmentation </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would also ask the select committee to consider how the English school system is being fragmented in a number of damaging ways.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A significant proportion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of schools are now governed by funding agreements with the secretary of state. The exact arrangements vary and are “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">based on the particular circumstances and political climate at the time and the reasons for the school’s creation”</span><a name="_ednref9"></a><a href="#_edn9">[ix]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">The consequence is that anyone seeking to raise an issue with a school (e.g.  admission appeals, SEN places, exclusions etc.) needs to identify exactly what provisions apply to the school in question. It has become more difficult for parents and childre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">n to get issues addressed local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">ly. They may have to go to the S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">ecretary of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">tate for a decision.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In addition local collaborative arrangements between schools are breaking down in many    areas</span><a name="_ednref10"></a><a href="#_edn10">[x]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In practice this means that arrangements for the placemen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t and support for disadvantaged and at risk pupils are no longer working properly. It also means that local planning designed to secure a broad 14 to 19 offer across an area is being undermined.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">9</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusions</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SEA believes that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the experiment with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unplanned marketization and privatisation of the school system has r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">un its course and that it is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> necessary to:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Restore to local communities a proper stake in the running of their schools</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Restore the notion of schooling as a public service rather than a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">private good</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Give schools the professional freedom they need to do their job well</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Provide for more effective monitoring of school performance</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Establish a comprehensive framework for school improvement</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Massively simplify the administration of schools</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Notes and References</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">see a number of contributions to </span><a href="http://www.localschoolsnetwork.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.localschoolsnetwork.org.uk</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn2"></a><a href="#_ednref2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Machin and Silva, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">School Structure, School Autonomy and the Tail – at </span><a href="http://cep.lse.ac.uk/pubs/download/special/cepsp29.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://cep.lse.ac.uk/pubs/download/special/cepsp29.pdf</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn3"></a><a href="#_ednref3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/09/04/pupils-segregation-class-race-sc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hools_n_3864512.html?utm_hp_ref=uk</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn4"></a><a href="#_ednref4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Equity and Quality in Education: Supporting Disadvantaged Students and Schools” (OECD 2012) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn5"></a><a href="#_ednref5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Two examples of the impact of uncontrolled free school developments: </span><a href="http://www.northtyneside.gov.uk/browse.shtml?p_subjectCategory=1567"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">http://www.northtyneside.gov.uk/browse.shtml?p_subjectCategory=1567</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">  sets out the local authority view of the free school controversy in North Tyneside.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a href="ht